I have a confession to make. When I returned from the war, I was not mistreated, nor was I reviled personally. The result was skepticism concerning reports of spitting at airports, etc. I had not seen these incidents and had never seen photos of such things in the numerous periodicals of our time.<br><br>
Bob Greene's book, _Homecoming_ dealt with the subject, yet 1/2 of the Veterans in his book felt the same as me - they disbelieved because it was not their personal experience.<br><br>
Since coming online almost two years ago, I have witnessed the occasional hatred towards vets, who served their country. What the perpetrators fail to realize is their taunts and jeers and cries of &quot;Baby Killer&quot; disparage *all who served* - even though their intention is to harm one or two people.<br><br>
When we have dialogue that makes plain the real existence of such people, it is paramount to historic accuracy to include these messages in total.<br><br>
As a veteran of combat in Vietnam, I have never denied that there existed a dark side of our role there. War is comprised of darkness. All wars. The returning vet of the Vietnam era has been characterized as being somehow &quot;diffent&quot;. A monstrosity. <br><br>
I can not speak for my fellow vets, but I will say that we take responsibility for events that occurred there because our consciences dictate that we must. This is expressed in a variety of ways. An awareness of common sense on the part of students of the war who read this site precludes me from listing them. I encourage students to thoroughly read this site. Completeness of information will be available ONLY if it is not subject to arbitrary censorship.<br><br>
The comments of thread #20 need to posted here. Let the readers of this site decide for themselves what they want to believe.
